<p>When the distance traveled by the delivery robot is extremely small, the incremental arc length 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm12">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi mathvariant="script">Δ</mi>
     <mi>S</mi>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> is equivalent to a small straight line of length 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm13">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi mathvariant="script">Δ</mi>
     <mi>d</mi>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>. The following formula can be deduced from 
 <xref ref-type="fig" rid="sensors-19-04980-f003">Figure 3</xref>b. 
 <disp-formula id="FD5-sensors-19-04980">
  <label>(5)</label>
  <math id="mm14">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi mathvariant="script">Δ</mi>
     <mi>x</mi>
     <mo>=</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="script">Δ</mi>
     <mi>d</mi>
     <mi>cos</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
     <mi>θ</mi>
     <mo>+</mo>
     <mfrac>
      <mrow>
       <mi mathvariant="script">Δ</mi>
       <mi>θ</mi>
      </mrow>
      <mn>2</mn>
     </mfrac>
     <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula>
 <disp-formula id="FD6-sensors-19-04980">
  <label>(6)</label>
  <math id="mm15">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi mathvariant="script">Δ</mi>
     <mi>y</mi>
     <mo>=</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="script">Δ</mi>
     <mi>d</mi>
     <mi>sin</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
     <mi>θ</mi>
     <mo>+</mo>
     <mfrac>
      <mrow>
       <mi mathvariant="script">Δ</mi>
       <mi>θ</mi>
      </mrow>
      <mn>2</mn>
     </mfrac>
     <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula>
</p>
